<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: HANOI; A NEIGHBORHOOD VISIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Only a few months ago, Vietnam and China were exchanging bellicose threats 
based on their respective claims to the isolated Spratly Islands in the South 
China Sea.But on Saturday, Chinese President Jiang Zemin is scheduled to arrive 
in Hanoi for a "good neighbor" round of meetings with senior Vietnamese 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
 The visit by Jiang symbolizes the ambiguity of Sino-Vietnamese relations. 
Regarding the Spratlys, the desolate archipelago that sits above what 
geologists claim may be a vast reserve of oil, the two enemies talk tough. 
Diplomatically, however, the Chinese and Vietnamese have made steady progress 
since normalizing relations in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
