<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; U.S. 
SUPREME COURT REJECTS APPEAL BY EX-LAPD OFFICIAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The U.S. Supreme Court declined Monday to hear an appeal by an ex-assistant 
Los Angeles police chief who sued the city over an investigation into whether 
his religious beliefs affected his job performance.  
</P>
<P>
 Robert Vernon, an elder in Sun Valley's Grace Community Church, said the 1991 
Police Commission-ordered probe hindered his ability to practice his religion. 
</P>
<P>
 He was in charge of the Los Angeles Police Department's Office of Operations 
under former Police Chief Daryl F. Gates from 1978 to June, 1992.  
</P>
<P>
 "I am very disappointed that the court declined to hear my case, where my 
career and reputation were destroyed by religious bigotry," Vernon said in a 
statement released by his attorney.  
</P>
<P>
 Attorney David Casterline said "the Supreme Court's declination to grant a 
review sets a dangerous precedent affecting all public employees and religious 
persons."  
</P>
<P>
 But Los Angeles City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky said the nation's highest 
court validated the decision to look into the allegations about Vernon.  
</P>
<P>
 Yaroslavsky was named as a defendant in Vernon's lawsuit, along with the city, 
City Council and then-Police Commissioners Jesse Brewer, Stanley Sheinbaum and 
Melanie Lomax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
