<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: SAN CLEMENTE; ATTEMPTED BREAK-INS PROMPT WARNINGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Residents are being warned to keep their windows and doors locked at night 
after a series of early morning burglary attempts over the past five months, 
along with one incident in which a woman was threatened by a knife-wielding 
intruder in her bedroom. 
</P>
<P>
 Orange County sheriff's spokesperson Jan Sener said there have been at least 
five attempted break-ins since July, all in San Clemente east of the Interstate 
5. 
</P>
<P>
 In most cases, residents have awakened in the morning to find doors and 
windows ajar. But last July, one San Clemente woman woke up to find a strange 
man in her house. 
</P>
<P>
 Sener said the man grabbed the woman from behind and threatened her with a 
knife before fleeing. 
</P>
<P>
 Sener said investigators aren't sure if the crimes are being committed by the 
same person. All of the break-in attempts have taken place between 1 and 5:30 
a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 In each case, including the knife assault, residents had left their window or 
door open. 
</P>
<P>
 "Many burglaries happen during the day," said Sener. "But these are occurring 
during the early morning hours." 
</P>
<P>
 Anyone with information about the crimes is asked to call the San Clemente 
police investigations division at (714) 361-8220. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents who want help to plan home security can contact Sener at (714) 
361-8213. FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
