<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY REVIEW: PIONEER ELECTRONIC FILES SUIT AGAINST TECHNICOLOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JACK SEARLES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Technicolor Videocassette Inc., based in Camarillo, has vowed to defend itself 
"vigorously" against a patent-infringement lawsuit filed in connection with the 
firm's fast-growing compact-disc duplicating unit. 
</P>
<P>
 The suit, filed by Discovision Associates, an Irvine-based subsidiary of 
Japan's giant Pioneer Electronic Corp., charges Technicolor with infringing on 
three of Discovision's U. S. patents in manufacturing and duplicating CDs and 
CD-ROMs.Discovision seeks unspecified damages and an injunction against further 
infringement. 
</P>
<P>
 CDs are the fastest-selling audio recordings. CD-ROMs look like CDs but can 
combine audio, video and text content. Technicolor has turned out millions of 
both kinds of items since starting to produce them in April for music 
distributors and others. 
</P>
<P>
 Dennis Fischel, Discovision's president and chief executive, says Technicolor 
Videocassette, a subsidiary of Technicolor Inc., has refused to enter into a 
licensing agreement. He says his company manages a worldwide portfolio of 1,400 
patents related to optical disc technology, the industry term for CD and CD-ROM 
production. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our policy is to make this technology widely available and to seek a return 
on our investment by licensing our patents on reasonable terms," Fischel said. 
"It's only fair to bring these proceedings against Technicolor Videocassette 
because we have a responsibility to our current licensees who are paying 
license fees." 
</P>
<P>
 But John H. Oliphant, Technicolor Inc.'s senior vice president for legal 
affairs, says management at the Camarillo plant was assured by outside advisers 
that its production line would not infringe on patents belonging to Discovision 
or any other firm. "When Discovision raised the issue, we asked which patents 
they were referring to and they refused to be specific," Oliphant said. "Then, 
without warning, they filed suit." 
</P>
<P>
 Oliphant said Technicolor will "defend ourselves vigorously" against the 
action, filed earlier this month in U. S. District Court in Delaware. 
</P>
</TEXT>
