<HEADLINE>
<P>
BODY WATCH; TIDBITS; EXCESS POUNDAGE WEIGHS US DOWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE KNOWLTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Here are some weighty facts to chew on: 
</P>
<P>
 * At any moment, 80 million Americans are trying to lose weight. 
</P>
<P>
 * Americans spend $30 billion-$50 billion annually in efforts to lose weight. 
</P>
<P>
 * Americans collectively have gained weight over the past decade, with a mean 
weight gain of about eight pounds. 
</P>
<P>
 * The economic costs of illness associated with overweight are estimated to be 
more than $45 billion annually. 
</P>
<P>
 * Overweight has been linked to health problems including heart disease, 
certain cancers, stroke, diabetes and high blood pressure. 
</P>
<P>
 * Efforts to lose weight are linked to health problems, including anorexia, 
bulimia, bone loss in women, drug abuse, nutritional deficiencies, injuries and 
death. 
</P>
<P>
 * Weight cycling (losing weight and putting it back on) is harmful to one's 
health. 
</P>
<P>
 * Body fat established during childhood influences health status later in 
life. 
</P>
<P>
 Sources: U.S. Department of Health and Human Services; National Center for 
Health Statistics; American Health Foundation; Healthy Weight Journal. LESLIE 
KNOWLTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
