<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROPERTY VALUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RON GALPERIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Postscript: My column last week on "Finding the Funds to Fix Quake Damage" 
generated a great deal of interest. But I received several calls from readers 
who were frustrated because some of the funding sources mentioned in the column 
weren't easily available.Several readers, for example, called the Community 
Development Commission of Los Angeles County -- which seemed unfamiliar with 
its own assistance programs. I subsequently called the commission and advised 
it to read its brochure, "Owner-Occupied Home Improvement Program." The 
commission, in turn, suggested that callers talk to FEMA first. It's no wonder 
some callers felt that they were being led in circles. 
</P>
<P>
 But I did make a mistake. The Gas Co. -- which in July launched a Community 
Partnership for Earthquake Repair program -- is not making loans available to 
earthquake victims. It is only repair aid and services that are being offered 
to qualified low-income, elderly and disabled residents, such as providing work 
crews to repair stucco walls, doors, stoves, damaged chimneys and the 
weatherstripping of a home. Those interested in this help should call (800) 
331-7593. 
</P>
</TEXT>
